Biography
 Thomas Kaplan started his career as an advisor to hedge funds in the field of strategic forecasting. He founded Apex Silver Mines in 1993 and served as its Chairman and CEO until 2004. He became the largest investor in African Platinum in 2003. In 2007, African Platinum was acquired by Impala Platinum for a reported $580 million. Also co-founded Leor Exploration & Production in 2003; in 2007, Leor's natural gas assets, Leor Energy, were sold to EnCana Oil & Gas USA, a subsidiary of Encana Corporation, for ...
Contact us to see more Biography
Education History

Institution Name:
University of Oxford
Qualification Name:
Master's degree
Education Type:
Graduate
Start Date:
 
End Date:
 

Contact us to see more Education History
Interesting Facts
Kaplan reportedly paid about $3.8 million for a rare oak and glass table, whose estimated presale price was $150,000 to $200,000. The table was made by the mid-century Italian designer, Carlo Mollino and the price that Kaplan paid was nearly two times the previous auction record price for a piece of 20th-century furniture.
Contact us to see more Interesting Facts
Interests, Passion, Hobbies

Kind of Interests, Passion and Hobbies: Politics
Description: Generous political donor gives to both sides of the political aisle. Lifetime giving exceeds $110,000. 


Kind of Interests, Passion and Hobbies: Environment
Description: Is a passionate environmentalist; donates to various nonprofit organizations, which support environmental causes.


Kind of Interests, Passion and Hobbies: Finance - Investment
Description: Has invested about $2 billion in gold and silver mines and companies. He has said that he has gone "All-In on Gold."

Contact us to see more Interests, Passion, Hobbies
Philanthropy

Giving Profile: Kaplan is a generous philanthropist; gives primarily to education, wildlife conservation and health-related causes. Recipients include the Lillian Jean Kaplan Foundation, Colorado School of Mines, Mount Sinai Hospital and 92nd Street Y. Co-founded Panthera for wild cat conservation. Panthera launched a $200 Million Initiative for Wild Cats to conserve the world's wild cats and their ecosystems. Established 92nd Street Y's Recanati-Kaplan Program for Excellence in the Arts. The program provides full, year-long scholarships based on artistic merit for children and teens to study. Is the Founder of The Orianne Society. In 2014, the foundation had assets exceeding $5.9 million and donated more than $1 million; gives primarily to education and environmental causes. Recipients include: Nature Conservancy, University of Florida, University of Massachusetts and the University of Georgia Research Foundation. The Kaplan family has provided financial support to the Lillian Jean Kaplan Foundation, named after Kaplan's mother. Also funded the Lillian Jean Kaplan Renal Transplantation Center at the University of Miami and a variety of prizes and grants for medical science research. Kaplan co-established the Buchanan-Kaplan Scholarship Fund at the Colorado School of Mines with a $1 million contribution to support non-U.S. students. With wife has reportedly endowed millions of dollars to Oxford University and launched a new diploma and new facilities at Oxford University's Wildlife Conservation Research Unit (WildCRU). In recognition of their support, WildCRU's base has been renamed The Recanati-Kaplan Centre. Also established the Kaplan Awards for Excellence in Medicine at the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai. The award is given to those faculty members who excel in training the next generation, provide high quality clinical care and conduct innovative research. The Kaplan couple personally pays 100% of the administrative costs of The Orianne Society and Panthera so that all donations go directly to the field to fund projects. In July 2015, Kaplan donated the $5 million gathered from the sale of his Mark I Spitfire P9374, a World War II air force plane, to charity.

Contact us to see more Philanthropy
